<br>
&quot;A &quot;rotation mob&quot; does not have to currently have a rotation in effect on it to be considered a mob eligible for rotation.&quot;<br>
<br>
Nice attempt at semantic sleight-of-hand.<br>
<br>
It it were a &quot;rotation mob&quot; it would be on rotation and inherently eligible for rotation.<br>
<br>
No one would dispute this.  However, being eligible for rotation is not the same thing as being a rotation mob.  In your list of what makes a rotation mob you left out something, that there is actual contention for the mob and guilds actually want a rotation set up for the mob.<br>
<br>
A woman may be eligible for marriage, that is a vastly different thing from being married.  Or to paraphrase you in  this context 'A &quot;married woman&quot; does not have to be married to be considered eligible for marriage.'<br>
What sense does that make? <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/btherathetravelagency.showUserPublicProfile?gid=travaill>travaill</A> at: 3/2/03 3:23:33 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#222222><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/btherathetravelagency.showUserPublicProfile?gid=extrafth>Extrafth</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Altus Domini</span><br>  Posts: 43<br> <font color=#00FFFF>(3/2/03 7:53 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ftherathetravelagencyfrm50.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=534.topic&index=224>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Teamwork</span><hr size=1> I read the first page of this, and didn't bother to read the rest, but I would like to say something if it's already been said I am sorry, just read the first page.<br>
